  "doc_id": "40476",
  "text": "Motility of these two species was quite distinct, but remarkably similar to motility patterns observed in stages of the schistosome life cycle. The difference reflects the physiological difference between motility based on muscular contractions and ciliary movement. The wiggling motility patterns of Turbartrix aceti and schistosome cercaria were similar and could be expressed in terms of frequency and amplitude (see below). The swimming pattern of schistosome miracidia resembled that of Paramecium, although the trajectories of the two organisms were distinct. The miracidia moved in an almost linear path with a mean speed of 225.0 µm/s, whereas Paramecium trajectories had a wavy shape, likely to reflect a spiral motion [CITATION_1] similar to the motility patterns described for sperm and other 3D microswimmers [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The waveforms seen apparently represent a helical path and the rotational speed is deductible from the time interval between two maximal readings. Interpretation of the wave forms as 2D representations of 3D motion give us the rotational speeds. For track 25, four waves are seen in 6 s, which corresponds to 0.67 rps i.e., 40 rpm. Track 16:~9/6 s ě 90 rpm, track 5:10/9 s ě 66 rpm, track 36: 5/5 s ě 60rpm, T22~10/11 ě 54rpm.",
